{"element":{"atomicNumber":108,"symbol":"Hs","name":"Hassium","wikidataId":"Q1252","wikipediaTitle":"Hassium","wikipediaUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hassium","period":7,"group":8,"block":"d","category":"transition metal","phase":"solid","mass":269.1336,"electronegativity":null,"ionizationEnergy":null,"radius":null,"summary":"Hassium is a synthetic chemical element; it has symbol Hs and atomic number 108. It is highly radioactive: its most stable known isotopes have half-lives of about ten seconds. One of its isotopes, 270Hs, has magic numbers of protons and neutrons for deformed nuclei, giving it greater stability against spontaneous fission. Hassium is a superheavy element; it has been produced in a laboratory in very small quantities by fusing heavy nuclei with lighter ones. Natural occurrences of hassium have been hypothesized but never found.","neighbors":["Bh","Mt"],"rankings":{"mass":12,"electronegativity":0,"ionizationEnergy":0,"radius":0,"density":0,"meltingPoint":0,"boilingPoint":0,"halfLife":30},"sources":{"structured":{"provider":"PubChem","license":"public domain","url":"https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/element/108"},"identifiers":{"provider":"Wikidata","license":"CC0 1.0","url":"https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q1252"},"summary":{"provider":"Wikipedia","title":"Hassium","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hassium","license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","accessDate":"2026-03-30"}},"discoveryYear":1984,"discoverer":"Peter Armbruster & Gottfried Münzenberg","etymologyOrigin":"place","etymologyDescription":"Latin Hassia: Hesse, the German state","density":null,"meltingPoint":null,"boilingPoint":null,"halfLife":12},"group":{"n":8,"label":"Group 8","description":"Iron, ruthenium, osmium, and hassium make up group 8. Iron is the most abundant transition metal on Earth and the cornerstone of steel production.","elements":["Fe","Ru","Os","Hs"]},"anomalies":[{"slug":"synthetic-heavy","label":"Synthetic superheavy elements","elementCount":15}],"nav":{"prevInGroup":{"symbol